208
00:15:45,683 --> 00:15:45,843
Yes.

209
00:15:46,455 --> 00:15:46,815
Okay, good.

210
00:15:46,996 --> 00:15:50,319
I wasn't sure if it would go away when I changed the tab.

211
00:15:50,839 --> 00:16:02,251
I tried getting walking directions from one side of the street basically to the other because Google walking directions won't tell you to cross in the middle of the block where there's no crosswalk.

212
00:16:02,331 --> 00:16:03,392
It sends you to a crosswalk.

213
00:16:04,133 --> 00:16:07,856
So you can see kind of how long

214
00:16:08,925 --> 00:16:14,546
of a distance it is to get to a crosswalk just to get from one side of the street to the other.

215
00:16:15,206 --> 00:16:25,208
So this is giving a distance of almost half a mile for a trip that really should be, you know, just over a third of that.

216
00:16:28,328 --> 00:16:35,469
And this was a pedestrian collision, but pedestrian issues apply to us too.

217
00:16:36,190 --> 00:16:37,790
And crosswalks are still

218
00:16:39,459 --> 00:16:41,360
are still a traffic calming measure.

219
00:16:45,482 --> 00:16:59,188
I don't know that there's necessarily much we need to do about this at the moment, but this is an important thing for us to keep in mind and to know about and to be aware about.

220
00:17:01,009 --> 00:17:02,830
Of course, it's a tragic thing to have happen.

221
00:17:04,013 --> 00:17:10,496
Um, but this road would seem to be a high priority for at least more crosswalks.

222
00:17:11,577 --> 00:17:21,181
Um, and, uh, since it's also potentially could be an alternative north-south route.

223
00:17:22,682 --> 00:17:29,205
And it's right on the Medford line too, but this could be an alternative north-south route to some potentially even bigger streets.

224
00:17:29,966 --> 00:17:32,287
So maybe this is a place to keep on our radar.

